:::summary
The electric telegraph was the first technology to separate communication from physical transportation, allowing a message to travel thousands of miles in seconds rather than days or weeks. Invented in the 1830s and 1840s, it shrank the world, transformed commerce and warfare, and laid the conceptual and physical groundwork for every modern communication technology — telephone, radio, and internet. The telegram, the brief message transmitted by telegraph, became the most important form of long-distance communication for nearly a century and shaped the way people thought, wrote, and conducted their affairs.
